","1322":"1322","1332":"1332","1387":"1387","1320":"1320","1276":"1276","1362":"1362","1319":"1319","1280":"1280","1390":"1390","1290":"1290","Haydock, Lancashire, England":"Haydock, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Warrington, Lancashire, England":"Warrington, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Houghton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","habitational name from any of numerous places called Houghton or Hoghton. Most of the placenames derive from Old English <i>hōh</i> ‘heel, spur of land’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’, though some have different etymologies; for example, Little Houghton in Eccles (Lancashire), which derives from Old English <i>halh</i> ‘nook, corner of land’ + <i>tūn</i>, and Houghton in Bigbury (Devon), which may derive from an Old English personal name <i>Huhha</i> + Old English <i>tūn</i>.","variant of   Haughton  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Haughton","meanings":["English: habitational name from Haughton (Cheshire, Lancashire, Northumberland, Shropshire, Staffordshire), or Haughton le Skerne (Durham). The placenames derive from Old English <i>halh</i> ‘nook, corner of land’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. Compare   Houghton  .","Irish: adopted for <b>Ó hEacháin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Eachán</i>’, a pet form of the personal name <i>Eachaidh</i> (see   Hoey  ).","Irish: adopted for <b>Ó hEachtair</b> ‘descendant of <i>Eachtair</i>’, a personal name of uncertain origin. Compare   Hoctor  ."]},{"name":"Howton","meanings":["English (London): variant of   Houghton  ."]},{"name":"Hufton","meanings":["English: habitational name; probably from Stony Houghton in Pleasley (Derbyshire), the name of which derives from Old English <i>hōh</i> ‘heel, spur of land’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. Compare   Houghton  ."]}]},{"name":"Emma","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, originally a short form of compound names such as   Ermintrude   containing the word <i>erm(en)</i>, <i>irm(en)</i> ‘entire’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, but its popularity in medieval England was greatly enhanced by the fact that it had been borne by the mother of Edward the Confessor, herself a Norman. In modern times, it was only in moderate use early in the 20th century but rose sharply in favour in the 1970s and has since remained perennially popular."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Emma de Houghton was born in 1304, in Haydock, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, her father, William de Houghton, was 28 and her mother, Mrs William Hoghton, was 24. She married Gilbert III de Haydock in 1319, in Haydock, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died in 1332, in Warrington, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 28."},"et":{"1304–1332":"1304–1332","1290–1362":"1290–1362","1322–1387":"1322–1387","1322–1390":"1322–1390","1276–1320":"1276–1320","1280–Female":"1280–Surnud","1304":"1304","1322":"1322","1332":"1332","1387":"1387","1320":"1320","1276":"1276","1362":"1362","1319":"1319","1280":"1280","13